Note:
==============================================================================
lab - CIE XYZ, CIELAB, and CIELCh Color Spaces
==============================================================================

This module implements the CIE 1931 XYZ tristimulus colour space and its
two derived perceptually-uniform spaces, CIELAB (1976) and CIELCh
(polar reformulation of LAB). The defining white point is D65 with
the Bradford-adapted sRGB primaries.

The forward sRGB -> XYZ pipeline:

    1. Apply sRGB inverse transfer function on each channel (handled by
       the caller via rgb.srgb_to_linear; this module accepts pre-linear
       inputs in xyz_from_linear_rgb).
    2. Multiply [r, g, b]^T by the sRGB -> XYZ matrix M (D65, Bradford):

           |  0.4124564  0.3575761  0.1804375 |
       M = |  0.2126729  0.7151522  0.0721750 |
           |  0.0193339  0.1191920  0.9503041 |

The CIELAB transform from XYZ:

           L* = 116 * f(Y / Yn) - 16
           a* = 500 * ( f(X / Xn) - f(Y / Yn) )
           b* = 200 * ( f(Y / Yn) - f(Z / Zn) )

with the nonlinear f(t):

           f(t) = t^(1/3)                       if  t > (6/29)^3
           f(t) = (1/3) * (29/6)^2 * t + 4/29    otherwise

This corresponds to f(t) = t^(1/3) for t > 0.008856 and
f(t) = 7.787*t + 16/116 otherwise, matching the CIE 15:2004 reference.

The CIELCh polar coordinates:

           C* = sqrt(a^2 + b^2)
           h  = atan2(b, a)  (in degrees, [0, 360))

Two perceptual distance metrics are exposed: CIE76 (the original
Euclidean distance in LAB) and CIEDE2000 (Sharma 2005 reference
implementation) including the L', C', h' rotation term and the SL, SC,
SH weighting functions.

References:
  - CIE 15:2004 "Colorimetry, 3rd Edition"
  - G. Sharma, W. Wu, E. N. Dalal, "The CIEDE2000 color-difference
    formula: Implementation notes, supplementary test data, and
    mathematical observations", Color Research & Application
    30(1), pp. 21-30, 2005
  - sRGB matrix from IEC 61966-2-1:1999 (D65, Bradford)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRUCT TYPE DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "ColorXyz":
    x as Float
    y as Float
    z as Float
End Type

Type called "ColorLab":
    l as Float
    a as Float
    b as Float
End Type

Type called "ColorLch":
    l as Float
    c as Float
    h as Float
End Type

Type called "ColorLuv":
    l as Float
    u as Float
    v as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NUMERIC HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "absf" takes v as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Floating-point absolute value.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Compare then negate.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single ucomisd plus negate.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If v is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0 minus v
    End If
    Return v
End Process

Process called "sqrtf" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Square-root delegating to arithmetic_core.sqrt which lowers to
    sqrtsd on x86-64.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single sqrt invocation.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~14 cycle latency on modern x86-64.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return Arith.sqrt(x)
End Process

Process called "cbrtf" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Real-valued cube root via Newton-Raphson on y^3 - x = 0. Used by the
    CIE LAB f(t) transform on the upper branch.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Sign-preserve, scale-reduce |x| into [1, 8] via halving / doubling
    by 8.0, then six Newton iterations from a polynomial seed.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 80 FLOPs total, dominated by the six iterations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure. Bounded iteration count.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let m be x
    If x is less than 0.0:
        Set sign to 0.0 minus 1.0
        Set m to 0.0 minus x
    End If
    If m is less than 0.000000000000000000000000000000001:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let y be 1.0
    Let scale_up be 0
    Let scratch be m
    While scratch is greater than 8.0:
        Set scratch to scratch divided by 8.0
        Set scale_up to scale_up plus 1
        If scale_up is greater than 400:
            Set scratch to 8.0
        End If
    End While
    Let scale_dn be 0
    While scratch is less than 1.0:
        Set scratch to scratch multiplied by 8.0
        Set scale_dn to scale_dn plus 1
        If scale_dn is greater than 400:
            Set scratch to 1.0
        End If
    End While
    Set y to scratch
    Let iter be 0
    While iter is less than 8:
        Let y2 be y multiplied by y
        Let num be (y2 multiplied by y) minus scratch
        Let den be 3.0 multiplied by y2
        If den is less than or equal to 0.0:
            Set iter to 8
        Otherwise:
            Set y to y minus (num divided by den)
            Set iter to iter plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let pow2 be 1.0
    Let iu be 0
    While iu is less than scale_up:
        Set pow2 to pow2 multiplied by 2.0
        Set iu to iu plus 1
    End While
    Let pow2_dn be 1.0
    Let id be 0
    While id is less than scale_dn:
        Set pow2_dn to pow2_dn multiplied by 2.0
        Set id to id plus 1
    End While
    Set y to (y multiplied by pow2) divided by pow2_dn
    Return sign multiplied by y
End Process

Process called "pow_real" takes base as Float, exponent as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Real-valued exponentiation via exp(y * ln(x)). Required by the
    CIEDE2000 weighting and rotation terms whose exponents (3.5, 25, 7,
    etc) are integer or half-integer values.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Range-reduce base into [1, 2) by repeated halving / doubling, sum
    the Mercator series for ln(m), multiply by exponent, then sum the
    Maclaurin series for exp(r). Output is reassembled with 2^n
    scaling.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 70 FLOPs per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If exponent is equal to 0.0:
        Return 1.0
    End If
    If base is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let m be base
    Let k be 0
    While m is greater than or equal to 2.0:
        Set m to m divided by 2.0
        Set k to k plus 1
        If k is greater than 2048:
            Return 0.0
        End If
    End While
    Let kd be 0
    While m is less than 1.0:
        Set m to m multiplied by 2.0
        Set kd to kd plus 1
        If kd is greater than 2048:
            Return 0.0
        End If
    End While
    Let z be (m minus 1.0) divided by (m plus 1.0)
    Let z2 be z multiplied by z
    Let term be z
    Let ln_m be 0.0
    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than 30:
        Let denom be Arith.int_to_float((2 multiplied by idx) plus 1)
        Set ln_m to ln_m plus (term divided by denom)
        Set term to term multiplied by z2
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While
    Set ln_m to ln_m multiplied by 2.0
    Let ln2 be 0.69314718055994530941723212145817656807550013436025525412
    Let ln_base be ln_m plus (Arith.int_to_float(k) multiplied by ln2)
    Set ln_base to ln_base minus (Arith.int_to_float(kd) multiplied by ln2)
    Let y be exponent multiplied by ln_base
    Let n_floor be Arith.float_to_int(y divided by ln2)
    If y is less than 0.0:
        If Arith.int_to_float(n_floor) is greater than (y divided by ln2):
            Set n_floor to n_floor minus 1
        End If
    End If
    Let r_y be y minus (Arith.int_to_float(n_floor) multiplied by ln2)
    Let exp_r be 1.0
    Let s_term be 1.0
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 32:
        Set s_term to (s_term multiplied by r_y) divided by Arith.int_to_float(i)
        Set exp_r to exp_r plus s_term
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let two_n be 1.0
    If n_floor is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let nn be n_floor
        While nn is greater than 0:
            Set two_n to two_n multiplied by 2.0
            Set nn to nn minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Let nn be 0 minus n_floor
        While nn is greater than 0:
            Set two_n to two_n divided by 2.0
            Set nn to nn minus 1
        End While
    End If
    Return exp_r multiplied by two_n
End Process

Process called "sin_deg" takes deg as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Sine of an angle expressed in degrees. Required by the CIEDE2000
    rotation term and the LCh -> LAB conversion.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reduces the angle modulo 360, converts to radians, then sums the
    Taylor series sin(x) = x - x^3/6 + x^5/120 - x^7/5040 + ... to 13
    terms with reduction into [-pi, pi] first.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 30 multiplies per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure, bounded reduction.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let d be deg
    While d is greater than or equal to 360.0:
        Set d to d minus 360.0
    End While
    While d is less than 0.0:
        Set d to d plus 360.0
    End While
    Let pi_const be 3.14159265358979323846
    Let x be (d multiplied by pi_const) divided by 180.0
    If x is greater than pi_const:
        Set x to x minus (2.0 multiplied by pi_const)
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    Let term be x
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let n be 1
    While n is less than 28:
        Set result to result plus (sign multiplied by term)
        Set term to (term multiplied by x) multiplied by x
        Let denom1 be Arith.int_to_float((2 multiplied by n) plus 1)
        Let denom2 be Arith.int_to_float(2 multiplied by n)
        Set term to term divided by denom1
        Set term to term divided by denom2
        Set sign to 0.0 minus sign
        Set n to n plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "cos_deg" takes deg as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Cosine in degrees implemented via sin_deg(90 - x).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns sin_deg(90 - deg).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost as sin_deg.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return sin_deg(90.0 minus deg)
End Process

Process called "atan2_deg" takes y as Float, x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Two-argument arctangent in degrees, returning a value in [0, 360).
    Uses series reduction with octant dispatch for accuracy.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reduces |y/x| to t in [0, 1] via the identity
    atan(t) + atan(1/t) = pi/2 for |t| > 1, then folds t in (0.5, 1]
    through atan(t) = pi/4 + atan((t - 1)/(t + 1)) so the Maclaurin
    series argument magnitude never exceeds 0.5 (post-fold bound 1/3),
    giving full double-precision convergence at the 60-term cutoff.
    The final angle is assembled from the sign quadrant.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 50 FLOPs per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let pi_const be 3.14159265358979323846
    If x is equal to 0.0:
        If y is greater than 0.0:
            Return 90.0
        End If
        If y is less than 0.0:
            Return 270.0
        End If
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let abs_y be absf(y)
    Let abs_x be absf(x)
    Let t be abs_y divided by abs_x
    Let inverted be 0
    If t is greater than 1.0:
        Set t to 1.0 divided by t
        Set inverted to 1
    End If
    Let folded be 0
    If t is greater than 0.5:
        Set t to (t minus 1.0) divided by (t plus 1.0)
        Set folded to 1
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    Let term be t
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let n be 0
    Let t2 be t multiplied by t
    While n is less than 60:
        Let denom be Arith.int_to_float((2 multiplied by n) plus 1)
        Set result to result plus ((sign multiplied by term) divided by denom)
        Set term to term multiplied by t2
        Set sign to 0.0 minus sign
        Set n to n plus 1
    End While
    If folded is equal to 1:
        Set result to (pi_const divided by 4.0) plus result
    End If
    If inverted is equal to 1:
        Set result to (pi_const divided by 2.0) minus result
    End If
    If x is less than 0.0:
        If y is greater than or equal to 0.0:
            Set result to pi_const minus result
        Otherwise:
            Set result to (0.0 minus pi_const) plus result
        End If
    Otherwise:
        If y is less than 0.0:
            Set result to 0.0 minus result
        End If
    End If
    Let deg_val be (result multiplied by 180.0) divided by pi_const
    While deg_val is less than 0.0:
        Set deg_val to deg_val plus 360.0
    End While
    While deg_val is greater than or equal to 360.0:
        Set deg_val to deg_val minus 360.0
    End While
    Return deg_val
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: D65 WHITE POINT (Bradford-adapted, XYZ tristimulus)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "d65_white_x" returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    The X tristimulus of the CIE D65 illuminant when Y is normalised to 1.
    Value 0.95047 matches CIE 15:2004 and IEC 61966-2-1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Literal constant.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 0.95047
End Process

Process called "d65_white_y" returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Y tristimulus = 1.0 (definition of normalised D65).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Literal constant.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 1.0
End Process

Process called "d65_white_z" returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Z tristimulus = 1.08883.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Literal constant.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 1.08883
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: sRGB <-> XYZ (D65, Bradford-adapted matrix)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "linear_rgb_to_xyz_x" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Row 0 of the sRGB -> XYZ matrix multiplied by the linear-RGB vector.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Coefficients per IEC 61966-2-1 with Bradford adaptation to D65.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies, two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((0.4124564 multiplied by r) plus (0.3575761 multiplied by g)) plus (0.1804375 multiplied by b)
End Process

Process called "linear_rgb_to_xyz_y" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Row 1 of the sRGB -> XYZ matrix.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Coefficients per IEC 61966-2-1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies, two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((0.2126729 multiplied by r) plus (0.7151522 multiplied by g)) plus (0.0721750 multiplied by b)
End Process

Process called "linear_rgb_to_xyz_z" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Row 2 of the sRGB -> XYZ matrix.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Coefficients per IEC 61966-2-1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies, two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((0.0193339 multiplied by r) plus (0.1191920 multiplied by g)) plus (0.9503041 multiplied by b)
End Process

Process called "rgb_to_xyz" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float returns ColorXyz:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a non-linear sRGB triple (r, g, b in [0, 1]) to XYZ in the
    D65 white-point reference. Applies the sRGB inverse transfer function
    to each channel before the matrix multiply.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Linearises each channel via the IEC 61966-2-1 piecewise inverse
    transfer, then evaluates the three matrix rows.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three transfer evaluations dominate; matrix multiply adds 9 FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r_lin be srgb_to_linear_local(r)
    Let g_lin be srgb_to_linear_local(g)
    Let b_lin be srgb_to_linear_local(b)
    Let out be a value of type ColorXyz
    Set out.x to linear_rgb_to_xyz_x(r_lin, g_lin, b_lin)
    Set out.y to linear_rgb_to_xyz_y(r_lin, g_lin, b_lin)
    Set out.z to linear_rgb_to_xyz_z(r_lin, g_lin, b_lin)
    Return out
End Process

Process called "srgb_to_linear_local" takes c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Local sRGB inverse transfer used by the rgb_to_xyz pipeline. Kept
    private to lab.runa so the CIELAB conversion stack remains
    self-contained and can be linked without pulling in rgb.runa's full
    surface area when only XYZ / Lab / LCh / Luv conversions are needed.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Piecewise: c/12.92 for c<=0.04045 else ((c+0.055)/1.055)^2.4.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Toe branch is two FP ops; gamma branch dominated by pow_real.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let a be c
    If c is less than 0.0:
        Set sign to 0.0 minus 1.0
        Set a to 0.0 minus c
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    If a is less than or equal to 0.04045:
        Set result to a divided by 12.92
    Otherwise:
        Let inside be (a plus 0.055) divided by 1.055
        Set result to pow_real(inside, 2.4)
    End If
    Return sign multiplied by result
End Process

Process called "linear_to_srgb_local" takes c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Forward sRGB transfer function on a linear-RGB channel.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Piecewise: 12.92*c for c<=0.0031308 else 1.055*c^(1/2.4) - 0.055.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Toe branch is two FP ops; gamma branch dominated by pow_real.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let a be c
    If c is less than 0.0:
        Set sign to 0.0 minus 1.0
        Set a to 0.0 minus c
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    If a is less than or equal to 0.0031308:
        Set result to a multiplied by 12.92
    Otherwise:
        Let inv_gamma be 1.0 divided by 2.4
        Set result to (1.055 multiplied by pow_real(a, inv_gamma)) minus 0.055
    End If
    Return sign multiplied by result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XYZ -> sRGB (D65, Bradford-adapted inverse matrix)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "xyz_to_linear_rgb_r" takes x as Float, y as Float, z as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Row 0 of the inverse sRGB matrix (XYZ -> linear-RGB).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Coefficients per IEC 61966-2-1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies, two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((3.2404542 multiplied by x) minus (1.5371385 multiplied by y)) minus (0.4985314 multiplied by z)
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_linear_rgb_g" takes x as Float, y as Float, z as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Row 1 of the inverse sRGB matrix.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Coefficients per IEC 61966-2-1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies, two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ((0.0 minus 0.9692660) multiplied by x) plus (((1.8760108 multiplied by y) plus (0.0415560 multiplied by z)))
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_linear_rgb_b" takes x as Float, y as Float, z as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Row 2 of the inverse sRGB matrix.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Coefficients per IEC 61966-2-1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies, two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return (((0.0556434 multiplied by x) minus (0.2040259 multiplied by y)) plus (1.0572252 multiplied by z))
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_rgb" takes xyz as ColorXyz, out_rgb as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convert an XYZ tristimulus back to sRGB (non-linear), writing the
    four floats r, g, b, 1.0 into out_rgb at offsets 0/8/16/24.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Inverse matrix multiply followed by linear_to_srgb per channel.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Nine FLOPs for the matrix plus three transfer evaluations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller guarantees out_rgb has at least 32 bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r_lin be xyz_to_linear_rgb_r(xyz.x, xyz.y, xyz.z)
    Let g_lin be xyz_to_linear_rgb_g(xyz.x, xyz.y, xyz.z)
    Let b_lin be xyz_to_linear_rgb_b(xyz.x, xyz.y, xyz.z)
    Let r_srgb be linear_to_srgb_local(r_lin)
    Let g_srgb be linear_to_srgb_local(g_lin)
    Let b_srgb be linear_to_srgb_local(b_lin)
    Let _wr be store_float_at_lab(out_rgb, 0, clamp01_local(r_srgb))
    Let _wg be store_float_at_lab(out_rgb, 8, clamp01_local(g_srgb))
    Let _wb be store_float_at_lab(out_rgb, 16, clamp01_local(b_srgb))
    Let _wa be store_float_at_lab(out_rgb, 24, 1.0)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "clamp01_local" takes v as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Unit clamp used when writing channels back out.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two compares.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If v is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    If v is greater than 1.0:
        Return 1.0
    End If
    Return v
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CIELAB f(t) AND ITS INVERSE
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lab_f" takes t as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Nonlinear CIE LAB transform f(t). On the upper branch t > epsilon
    (where epsilon = 216/24389 = 0.008856...), returns cbrt(t). On the
    lower branch returns 7.787*t + 16/116. Used by xyz_to_lab.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Threshold at 0.008856 (216/24389). Below: linear with slope 7.787
    (= (24389/27) / 116, approximately) plus 16/116.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Branch + either cbrtf or two FP ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let epsilon be Arith.int_to_float(216) divided by Arith.int_to_float(24389)
    If t is greater than epsilon:
        Return cbrtf(t)
    End If
    Let kappa be Arith.int_to_float(24389) divided by Arith.int_to_float(27)
    Let slope be kappa divided by 116.0
    Let offset be 16.0 divided by 116.0
    Return (slope multiplied by t) plus offset
End Process

Process called "lab_f_inverse" takes ft as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of lab_f used by lab_to_xyz. The upper branch is the cube of
    ft (ft^3 > epsilon iff f(t) > delta where delta = 6/29).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Threshold at 6/29 = 0.20689655... above which we cube; below we
    invert the linear branch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One compare, two FP ops on each branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let delta be 6.0 divided by 29.0
    If ft is greater than delta:
        Return (ft multiplied by ft) multiplied by ft
    End If
    Let kappa be Arith.int_to_float(24389) divided by Arith.int_to_float(27)
    Let slope be kappa divided by 116.0
    Let offset be 16.0 divided by 116.0
    Return (ft minus offset) divided by slope
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_lab" takes xyz as ColorXyz returns ColorLab:
    @Reasoning
    Convert XYZ (D65 reference) to CIELAB. Divides by the D65 tristimulus
    component, applies f, and assembles L*, a*, b* per CIE 15:2004.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    L = 116 f(Y/Yn) - 16, a = 500 (f(X/Xn) - f(Y/Yn)),
    b = 200 (f(Y/Yn) - f(Z/Zn)).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three lab_f evaluations dominate.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let fx be lab_f(xyz.x divided by d65_white_x())
    Let fy be lab_f(xyz.y divided by d65_white_y())
    Let fz be lab_f(xyz.z divided by d65_white_z())
    Let out be a value of type ColorLab
    Set out.l to (116.0 multiplied by fy) minus 16.0
    Set out.a to 500.0 multiplied by (fx minus fy)
    Set out.b to 200.0 multiplied by (fy minus fz)
    Return out
End Process

Process called "lab_to_xyz" takes lab as ColorLab returns ColorXyz:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of xyz_to_lab.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    fy = (L + 16) / 116, fx = a / 500 + fy, fz = fy - b / 200, then apply
    lab_f_inverse to each and multiply by the D65 tristimulus.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three lab_f_inverse evaluations dominate.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let fy be (lab.l plus 16.0) divided by 116.0
    Let fx be (lab.a divided by 500.0) plus fy
    Let fz be fy minus (lab.b divided by 200.0)
    Let out be a value of type ColorXyz
    Set out.x to lab_f_inverse(fx) multiplied by d65_white_x()
    Set out.y to lab_f_inverse(fy) multiplied by d65_white_y()
    Set out.z to lab_f_inverse(fz) multiplied by d65_white_z()
    Return out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CIE 1976 L*u*v* COLOR SPACE
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "uv_prime_x" takes x as Float, y as Float, z as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    The CIE 1976 u' chromaticity coordinate per CIE 15:2004:
        u' = 4X / (X + 15Y + 3Z)
    Returns 0.0 when the denominator is non-positive (the achromatic
    axis at the origin has no defined chromaticity).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    One linear combination + one divide.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let denom be x plus ((15.0 multiplied by y) plus (3.0 multiplied by z))
    If denom is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Return (4.0 multiplied by x) divided by denom
End Process

Process called "uv_prime_y" takes x as Float, y as Float, z as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    The CIE 1976 v' chromaticity coordinate per CIE 15:2004:
        v' = 9Y / (X + 15Y + 3Z)
    Returns 0.0 when the denominator is non-positive.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    One linear combination + one divide.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three FLOPs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let denom be x plus ((15.0 multiplied by y) plus (3.0 multiplied by z))
    If denom is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Return (9.0 multiplied by y) divided by denom
End Process

Process called "luv_create" takes l as Float, u as Float, v as Float returns ColorLuv:
    @Reasoning
    Direct constructor for the CIE 1976 L*u*v* triple. No clamping: L
    above 100 is valid for HDR pipelines and u / v are intentionally
    unbounded for wide-gamut XYZ input.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Field assignment.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorLuv
    Set out.l to l
    Set out.u to u
    Set out.v to v
    Return out
End Process

Process called "xyz_to_luv" takes xyz as ColorXyz returns ColorLuv:
    @Reasoning
    Convert CIE 1931 XYZ (D65 reference) to CIE 1976 L*u*v* per
    CIE 15:2004. The L* coordinate inherits the LAB lightness so the
    luminance perception is consistent between the two spaces; u* and
    v* are L*-weighted differences of the input chromaticity from the
    D65 reference chromaticity:
        L* = 116 * f(Y / Yw) - 16
        u* = 13 * L* * (u' - u_w')
        v* = 13 * L* * (v' - v_w')
    where (u_w', v_w') is the D65 reference chromaticity computed at
    the canonical D65 tristimulus.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Computes u' / v' for the colour and for the D65 reference, applies
    the LAB f() to Y / Yw to recover L*, then forms the L*-weighted
    difference for u* / v*.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two divides + the lab_f evaluation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let u_prime be uv_prime_x(xyz.x, xyz.y, xyz.z)
    Let v_prime be uv_prime_y(xyz.x, xyz.y, xyz.z)
    Let u_prime_w be uv_prime_x(d65_white_x(), d65_white_y(), d65_white_z())
    Let v_prime_w be uv_prime_y(d65_white_x(), d65_white_y(), d65_white_z())
    Let yn be xyz.y divided by d65_white_y()
    Let fy be lab_f(yn)
    Let l_val be (116.0 multiplied by fy) minus 16.0
    Let out be a value of type ColorLuv
    Set out.l to l_val
    Set out.u to (13.0 multiplied by l_val) multiplied by (u_prime minus u_prime_w)
    Set out.v to (13.0 multiplied by l_val) multiplied by (v_prime minus v_prime_w)
    Return out
End Process

Process called "luv_to_xyz" takes luv as ColorLuv returns ColorXyz:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of xyz_to_luv. Recovers (X, Y, Z) at the D65 reference from
    a CIELUV triple via the rearrangement:
        Yn = ((L + 16) / 116)^3              if L > 8
        Yn = L / kappa                        otherwise
        u' = u / (13 L) + u_w'
        v' = v / (13 L) + v_w'
        X  = (9 Y u') / (4 v')
        Z  = (12 - 3 u' - 20 v') Y / (4 v')
    where kappa = 24389 / 27. At L = 0 the chromaticity is undefined and
    the function returns the origin.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Selects the cubic / linear branch of Yn per CIE 15:2004; handles
    the v' = 0 degenerate case by returning the origin (the only
    in-gamut point with zero chromaticity is the black tristimulus).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant cost (a handful of divides and multiplies).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorXyz
    Set out.x to 0.0
    Set out.y to 0.0
    Set out.z to 0.0
    If luv.l is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return out
    End If
    Let u_prime_w be uv_prime_x(d65_white_x(), d65_white_y(), d65_white_z())
    Let v_prime_w be uv_prime_y(d65_white_x(), d65_white_y(), d65_white_z())
    Let u_prime be (luv.u divided by (13.0 multiplied by luv.l)) plus u_prime_w
    Let v_prime be (luv.v divided by (13.0 multiplied by luv.l)) plus v_prime_w
    Let kappa be Arith.int_to_float(24389) divided by Arith.int_to_float(27)
    Let yn be 0.0
    If luv.l is greater than 8.0:
        Let t be (luv.l plus 16.0) divided by 116.0
        Set yn to (t multiplied by t) multiplied by t
    Otherwise:
        Set yn to luv.l divided by kappa
    End If
    Let y_val be yn multiplied by d65_white_y()
    Set out.y to y_val
    If v_prime is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return out
    End If
    Set out.x to ((9.0 multiplied by y_val) multiplied by u_prime) divided by (4.0 multiplied by v_prime)
    Let z_factor be (12.0 minus ((3.0 multiplied by u_prime) plus (20.0 multiplied by v_prime))) multiplied by y_val
    Set out.z to z_factor divided by (4.0 multiplied by v_prime)
    Return out
End Process

Process called "luv_l" takes c as ColorLuv returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Read the L* coordinate of a CIELUV triple.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Field read.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return c.l
End Process

Process called "luv_u" takes c as ColorLuv returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Read the u* coordinate of a CIELUV triple.
    @End Reasoning
